WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
My name is Logan Pratico. I'm a data engineer at the Legal Services Corporation, where I

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:19.040
work on a relatively new project called the Civil Court Data Initiative. So just to sort

00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:23.879
of start out and center this talk a little bit on the issues that I'm going to be discussing

00:00:23.879 --> 00:00:29.719
for the next 15 to 20 minutes, let's just start with, you know, what is the civil justice

00:00:29.719 --> 00:00:37.919
system? Civil court is somewhat different from criminal court, which I'm not sure, but

00:00:37.919 --> 00:00:41.400
I would imagine a lot of you all in this room are probably much more familiar with. That's

00:00:41.400 --> 00:00:45.880
going to be the things where, you know, you commit a crime like, you know, robbery or

00:00:45.880 --> 00:00:51.360
something like that. You're often arrested by a police officer. You go to court. You

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:57.200
plead guilty or not guilty. You're handed a verdict and then you go to jail. Civil court

00:00:57.200 --> 00:01:01.599
is a different side of that, right? So civil court is going to be the things that you're

00:01:01.599 --> 00:01:06.720
going to appear in court for, but where you didn't necessarily commit a crime. So this

00:01:06.720 --> 00:01:09.779
is going to be things like eviction, which is going to be the focus of what I'm talking

00:01:09.779 --> 00:01:20.480
about today, but also things like debt collection, guardianship, you know, cases like that, right?

00:01:20.480 --> 00:01:27.639
These areas are slightly different, but in a lot of ways they can be equally as harrowing.

00:01:27.639 --> 00:01:36.220
So for eviction, for example, what happens in these cases can uproot a fundamental human

00:01:36.220 --> 00:01:42.320
right for a lot of individuals, their right to shelter, their right to a home. It can

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:50.760
leave folks with forcing them to leave their sense of community, their sense of belonging.

00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:56.760
A lot of their possessions are often left behind into sort of a world of uncertainty

00:01:56.760 --> 00:02:01.279
where you don't necessarily know where you're going to be sleeping next or where you're

00:02:01.279 --> 00:02:08.720
going to be just at home next. The organization that I work for, Legal Services Corporation,

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:17.800
was stood up in the 1970s because, with the explicit purpose to provide legal assistance

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:25.080
to individuals that are navigating this system, because a key difference between criminal

00:02:25.080 --> 00:02:30.919
and civil court is that folks aren't guaranteed the right to a lawyer. So that classic image

00:02:30.919 --> 00:02:33.960
that you all might have for something like law and order, where a person's Miranda rights

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:38.119
are being read and they're being told that if you can't afford a lawyer, one will be

00:02:38.119 --> 00:02:43.880
appointed to you, that doesn't happen in civil court. Individuals are often left to

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:51.559
navigate an incredibly complex legal process entirely unassisted. And so our goal is to

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:57.720
essentially provide funding to legal aid organizations across the country that work to represent

00:02:57.720 --> 00:03:05.119
these individuals who qualify in court. Now, the project that I work on within Legal Services

00:03:05.119 --> 00:03:12.119
Corporation is known as the Civil Court Data Initiative. And we essentially believe that

00:03:12.119 --> 00:03:19.559
court data, when standardized and analyzed in aggregate, can be an incredibly powerful

00:03:19.559 --> 00:03:27.779
tool in helping to allocate limited resources and finite time for these legal aid organizations

00:03:27.779 --> 00:03:33.720
working on the ground. So you can see here is our current map of coverage. This was taken

00:03:33.720 --> 00:03:39.600
from our website, which you can find the URL up in the corner there. And the first

00:03:39.600 --> 00:03:43.080
thing you might notice is that there's a lot of white on the screen. That's because we

00:03:43.080 --> 00:03:49.600
don't have all of the data yet. We have a lot of states for which we just don't know

00:03:49.600 --> 00:03:55.479
what the eviction landscape looks like. To put that in context, imagine if we just couldn't

00:03:55.479 --> 00:04:02.520
say how many people died of heart disease every year. Imagine what that would mean for

00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:09.839
policy and just general decisions from, you know, in the medical field, all of that. That's

00:04:09.839 --> 00:04:15.100
what the eviction landscape certainly looked like in 2019 when this map was completely

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:21.279
white. And in a lot of ways, what it still looks like today. Our goal is to be able to

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:25.600
answer questions like, you know, or to be able to say things like, you know, how many

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:31.760
folks, how many individuals in Virginia are facing eviction of all renters? And the answer

00:04:31.760 --> 00:04:36.600
might surprise you. There were relative to the number of renter households in the state

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:41.959
of Virginia, there were about 12% of those were facing eviction filings. These numbers

00:04:41.959 --> 00:04:50.559
are high. And that's sort of what we're trying to present with collecting this data. To get

00:04:50.559 --> 00:04:58.079
technical for a second, and not too technical, we have our data pipeline essentially looks

00:04:58.119 --> 00:05:03.000
like this. And this is pretty simplified. But this is the basic idea. We have a data

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:09.440
source, which for us can be court websites, bulk data downloads. You know, there are only

00:05:09.440 --> 00:05:16.160
three up here. But to put it into context, there are over 1,200 different unique jurisdictions

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:22.839
across the entire country. And we're working to basically collect all of that data and

00:05:22.839 --> 00:05:30.799
aggregate it into a standardized system. We use a variety of sort of cutting edge data

00:05:30.799 --> 00:05:37.760
orchestration platforms like DBT and Prefect and AWS services. The list goes on and it

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:43.359
would make me sound smarter than I am to just sort of say them out loud. But the end goal

00:05:43.359 --> 00:05:50.000
is to kind of just have a set of standardized data sets that we can put in a data lake.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:57.399
And this is, you know, overall relatively simple. The idea is to basically just have

00:05:57.399 --> 00:06:03.920
queryable data that our team of research analysts and other folks can use. It can be incredibly

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:09.839
complicated to do that standardization. But the end goal is to essentially just have databases

00:06:09.839 --> 00:06:16.279
that are accessible to folks. And what our data pipeline looked like for a while was

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:21.720
that we were basically just subsetting that data and providing it to the end user, the

00:06:21.720 --> 00:06:29.239
legal aid organizations. This pretty much exclusively, when we were first starting out,

00:06:29.239 --> 00:06:36.839
took the form of just spreadsheets. Really boring stuff, to be completely honest. I mean,

00:06:36.839 --> 00:06:44.200
I know that a lot of folks in this room are familiar with, you know, R and other data

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:49.359
science tools. And you might look at a data set like this and say, there's a lot that

00:06:49.359 --> 00:06:54.440
I can do with that. It's standardized. It's in a long format. You know, ported into R.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:58.760
And you could have some visualizations going. You know, there's a lot of fun stuff that

00:06:58.760 --> 00:07:05.959
you can do with that. But remember, the folks that we're trying to get this data to aren't

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:11.760
data scientists. They're lawyers. They don't come from that computer science or data science

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:18.920
or even just any sort of coding background. They've spent their lives in courts studying

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:24.600
legal text. In the same way that if you were to ask me, you know, can you tell me what

00:07:24.600 --> 00:07:29.200
like, can you just read this legalese and interpret it? And I would, you know, look

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:36.359
at you with wide eyes. The same thing kind of happens, you know, if you give someone

00:07:36.359 --> 00:07:40.559
with a legal background a spreadsheet and basically say, you know, answer whatever question

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:45.200
you have. But that's kind of what we wanted to do, is we wanted to be able to provide

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:49.600
folks with the tools to answer questions that they had. We didn't really want to answer

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:55.359
questions for them. We just wanted to, or tell them, rather, tell them what questions

00:07:55.359 --> 00:08:03.799
they had and provide the answers. We wanted these folks to be able to basically, you know,

00:08:03.799 --> 00:08:10.600
answer questions that were specific to their context. A story that I like to tell with

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:17.160
this, or I don't really like to tell, but I think it's a good example here, is that

00:08:17.160 --> 00:08:22.600
when we were using this method of basically just sending off data sets to different legal

00:08:22.600 --> 00:08:28.679
aid organizations, we had for a particular grantee, a particular legal aid organization

00:08:28.679 --> 00:08:36.159
that we were working with, we had sent them a data set, and we uploaded it to Box, just

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:44.039
as a, it was our file sharing platform. And we, you know, emailed it, sent it off. Didn't

00:08:44.039 --> 00:08:48.200
really hear back for about two weeks. And then in a team meeting, we were, you know,

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:52.880
just internally talking about it, and we circled back. We thought, you know, whatever happened

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:58.119
with that, did they use it? And so we went back, and we looked at that Box link, and

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:01.479
we realized that we hadn't actually shared it externally. We had uploaded it to Box,

00:09:01.479 --> 00:09:06.719
but it was only shared within our organization. And so nobody could actually see it outside

00:09:06.719 --> 00:09:11.320
of us. And the people that were, the folks we were sharing it with never reached out

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:15.640
to us. They never asked us, you know, they never said, hey, you know, we clicked on the

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:21.479
link and we can't actually access it. And I think that, you know, what better way to

00:09:21.479 --> 00:09:26.520
show that, like, the data that you're sending off isn't being used or isn't important than

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:30.679
just the fact that, like, they can't, they didn't even try and access it, or they didn't,

00:09:30.679 --> 00:09:33.280
or maybe they tried to access it, and then when they couldn't, they didn't care enough

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:39.479
to actually follow up. So that was a real eye-opening moment for us when we kind of

00:09:39.479 --> 00:09:46.919
realized, you know, this data isn't actually being used. We're, we have this really complex

00:09:46.919 --> 00:09:52.479
pipeline going from court website all the way to standardized data sets. It's getting

00:09:52.479 --> 00:09:58.400
95% of the way there. But then we just weren't going the last 5%. And we weren't saying,

00:09:58.400 --> 00:10:02.919
you know, what is it that is actually going to help us to meet these legal aid organizations

00:10:02.919 --> 00:10:08.880
where they are and get them the data that they need. And that's when we sort of revised.

00:10:08.880 --> 00:10:13.840
And this was a little bit before the quarto phase. So I know that this is a little bit

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:20.280
crazy. So this is a little bit out of date. But we used our markdown to essentially generate

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:24.840
weekly reports that took the same data from the spreadsheets that I was showing you on

00:10:24.840 --> 00:10:32.320
the last page and just put it into a really easily readable, easily digestible format

00:10:32.320 --> 00:10:38.239
that answered surface-level questions, in our eyes, sort of the lowest common denominator

00:10:38.239 --> 00:10:44.440
of questions that you could answer across all of our court data. And we provided that

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:51.400
to our end users, to the legal aid organizations. You can see here are just a couple of examples.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:56.320
For Vermont, you can see, you know, it has a little bit, I'm not sure if you can read

00:10:56.320 --> 00:11:00.479
that text, but essentially what it says up there at the top is just a brief introduction.

00:11:00.479 --> 00:11:06.599
We collect data across 14 counties in Vermont. And this graph generated in ggplot just sort

00:11:06.599 --> 00:11:11.280
of shows, you know, that's what the landscape kind of looks like across the board. That's

00:11:11.320 --> 00:11:16.479
what eviction filings look like over the past year. Similarly, you have an outline for Connecticut

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:20.960
there that basically just shows, it's a heat map that just shows eviction filing hotspots.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:25.799
So areas in darker red are going to be areas that have the most eviction filings or more

00:11:25.799 --> 00:11:34.960
eviction filings than the areas in a lighter color red. So yeah, so I kind of alluded to

00:11:34.960 --> 00:11:41.679
this before, but the questions that we were answering were pretty basic or trying to answer

00:11:41.679 --> 00:11:45.960
with these memos that were only, you know, two pages in length and didn't really have

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:51.919
a lot of text. It was just, you know, what do eviction filing trends look like over the

00:11:51.919 --> 00:11:59.640
past year in a particular state? Or, you know, what counties have the most eviction filings?

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:04.679
As well, you know, how does representation differ between landlords and tenants in these

00:12:04.679 --> 00:12:10.919
cases? The answer might surprise you. It's wide. There is a huge disparity between representation

00:12:10.919 --> 00:12:17.520
for tenants and landlords. And really just, you know, in answering the, or in creating

00:12:17.520 --> 00:12:23.159
these memos, I just want to hammer the point home that we weren't trying to answer every

00:12:23.159 --> 00:12:29.039
question that they might have. Instead, which is something that we were doing with our previous

00:12:29.039 --> 00:12:34.840
data sets. Instead, we were just providing a taste of what we had with the data and welcoming

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:42.640
them to come back to us, the organizations to come back to us and ask us questions and

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:48.799
say things like, I had no, or I had some idea that my county had the highest rate of eviction

00:12:48.799 --> 00:12:56.039
filings in the entire state, but this confirms it. And I'd really like to, you know, know

00:12:56.159 --> 00:13:02.919
who the top filers are, who the top companies are that are evicting folks in my state, or

00:13:02.919 --> 00:13:08.520
what is the, what are the judgments? What are the outcomes of these cases? And what

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:19.719
does that look like? And so it took us from this data pipeline to a slightly revised version

00:13:19.719 --> 00:13:24.640
where we still had the data source and the data lake, but rather than going from standardized

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:31.679
data sets directly to the end user, essentially what we were doing was just going by way of,

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:37.400
you know, data memos for our markdown and passing that along. Again, this diagram is

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:42.919
a little bit oversimplistic in a way, because I think that it implies that we stopped sending

00:13:42.919 --> 00:13:50.960
data or spreadsheets, which isn't true. We had data memos, but we really used those as

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:56.000
just sort of a jumping off point, as a way to get the ball rolling, to get the conversation

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:04.359
going around sharing data. And what ended up happening is, like I said, folks came back

00:14:04.359 --> 00:14:09.359
to us and asked us, you know, can I have this data? And then the spreadsheets that we were

00:14:09.359 --> 00:14:16.400
sending them were things that were actually important, things that they actually wanted,

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:21.960
which is obviously always key when you're sending off data. We found that, you know,

00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:28.039
we went from sending off data that nobody had asked for and nobody was looking at, to

00:14:28.039 --> 00:14:32.640
folks actually, like, not being able to send data off fast enough. We had to grow our team

00:14:32.640 --> 00:14:37.000
because we couldn't respond to all of the specific data requests that we were getting,

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:44.679
which is always a great thing to do. And so some of the outcomes from this work,

00:14:44.679 --> 00:14:49.320
there were a couple of different things. Principally, we had improved data accessibility

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:55.520
and understanding. So, again, folks were no longer having to, you know, work in Excel

00:14:55.520 --> 00:15:01.760
to find an answer to their specific question. They could just have that analysis done for

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:11.200
them. This also improved access via just sharing the information directly. Beyond that, we

00:15:11.200 --> 00:15:15.400
had time efficiency. And this is both time efficiency on our end, because we weren't

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:20.799
coming up with custom data sets to send off in anticipation of a specific legal aid organization's

00:15:20.799 --> 00:15:26.719
needs. Instead, we were zooming out to the state level and automatically generating these

00:15:26.719 --> 00:15:32.280
reports. You know, we put them on, for those of you familiar with Amazon Web Services,

00:15:32.280 --> 00:15:37.239
we put them on an EC2 instance in Amazon Web Services and kind of just let it run in the

00:15:37.239 --> 00:15:43.159
cloud. And it does that every day, or excuse me, every week. So, every Monday, I log on

00:15:43.159 --> 00:15:49.200
to my computer and just sort of double check the output of the Word documents and make

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:54.159
sure that, you know, everything looks good. We also have more efficient tests that are

00:15:54.159 --> 00:16:01.119
running programmatically. But as a final check, that's really what I do every Monday is just

00:16:01.119 --> 00:16:04.719
over my cup of coffee, I look at each individual document and I make sure that it's looking

00:16:04.719 --> 00:16:08.799
good. And that's the extent of it. And then we can just sort of let them live there and

00:16:08.799 --> 00:16:16.599
share them and, you know, revisit things on a quarterly basis, rather than having to regenerate

00:16:16.599 --> 00:16:23.119
new documents every week or for every individual occasion. On the part of the legal aid organizations,

00:16:23.119 --> 00:16:33.760
again, not having to do the analysis with our data, that's a huge time saver. And then

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:37.880
the last thing is just increased conversation, which is really what our end goal is, is

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:45.280
to be able to talk to folks and, you know, get their insight of how the data can best

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:55.119
help them. And that's definitely a downstream of this. So, as a recap, aggregating, cleaning,

00:16:55.119 --> 00:17:00.239
standardizing this data was really sort of the first step in the process. But we thought

00:17:00.239 --> 00:17:05.920
that it was the whole process. We thought that just if we were going to be able to collect

00:17:05.920 --> 00:17:11.800
all of this disaggregate information and, you know, like people would naturally be interested

00:17:11.800 --> 00:17:17.839
in it. And that was something that we learned just isn't the case. Instead, we had to take

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:25.040
a less is more approach to answering more just superficial questions initially. But

00:17:25.040 --> 00:17:30.160
seeing that, you know, that would lead to increased conversation and more data sharing

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:36.599
down the road. And in the end, this really improved engagement and understanding of the

00:17:36.599 --> 00:17:42.839
data. So, thank you very much. I'll say that if you're interested in viewing the memos

00:17:42.839 --> 00:17:46.959
that I've been talking about, there is a QR code there that you can sort of scan that.

00:17:46.959 --> 00:17:55.079
But yeah, happy to answer any questions. Thank you.

00:17:55.079 --> 00:18:01.040
Thank you so much, Logan. We have time for at least one question. So, what are your planned

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:05.079
or aspirational next steps for data sharing with your stakeholders?

00:18:05.079 --> 00:18:13.040
Yeah, so that's an excellent question. So, I think that the big thing, right, is creating

00:18:13.040 --> 00:18:19.479
interactive visualizations in sort of like a dashboard format. So, we have our website,

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:25.599
which you can see at the URL there. And we have these static memos. But the website is

00:18:25.599 --> 00:18:30.760
more of a public facing, you know, that is very, both of these are very public facing,

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:36.599
which can limit the amount of data that we really want to publish on it because we don't

00:18:36.599 --> 00:18:43.160
want to just give out all of the data for security, privacy concerns. And so, the end

00:18:43.160 --> 00:18:50.560
goal would be to create a dashboard that allows specific folks like these grantee, we call

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:59.119
them grantees because we do fund them. That's the main work that LSC does, is to essentially

00:18:59.119 --> 00:19:04.119
provide them with information that way, sort of more privately.

00:19:04.119 --> 00:19:05.119
Thank you again.

00:19:05.119 --> 00:19:05.119


